   response, infrastructure inspection, and urban environmental monitoring.
   However, path planning for multi-UAV systems in such environments
   remains particularly challenging due to the presence of various threat
   zones, including obstacles, signal interference regions, and hazardous
   areas, which existing methods fail to address adequately. We present an
   enhanced grid-based modeling approach specifically designed for urban
   environments with distinct threat zones to bridge this gap. In addition,
   we propose an improved Multi-UAV Rapidly-exploring Random Tree Star
   (RRT{*}) algorithm integrated with Biased Sampling, Candidate Evaluation
   and Path Reconfiguration techniques (MU-RRT{*}-BCR). Specifically, the
   combination of biased sampling and candidate evaluation enhances node
   selection, reducing the average objective function value by 16.66\% and
   CPU time by 80.28\% compared to MU-RRT{*}. Additionally, a security
   detection mechanism is incorporated to prevent inter-UAV collisions.
   Moreover, a path reconfiguration technique is employed to refine the UAV
