Month = {OCT 1},
Abstract = {Unmanned aerial vehicles (UAVs) have gained significant popularity in
   both military and civilian sectors due to their maneuverability and
   versatility. However, their reliance on global navigation satellite
   systems (GNSSs) for real-time and precise navigation makes them
   vulnerable to interference, particularly in hostile jamming
   environments. In this article, we present a novel approach to address
   the challenges posed by GNSS jamming in UAVs navigation. Unlike
   traditional multisensor fusion techniques, our method focuses on
   physically combining signals from multiple homogeneous sensors,
   extending centralized multiantenna anti-jamming techniques to
   cooperative distributed scenarios. This approach leverages frequency
   conversion and forwarding to bypass GNSS navigation band, enabling
   signal aggregation. Using multiple UAVs, it enhances system resilience
   and spatial degrees of freedom (DoFs), achieving both anti-jamming and
   collaborative navigation objectives simultaneously. Theoretical analysis
   demonstrates the feasibility and potential of this technique in ensuring
   precise and secure UAV operations in GNSS-jamming environments.},
